    Mira, humbled, played—not the commanding melodies of old, but a soft, wordless hum, born of her sorrow. The eagle listened, and when the last note faded, it released Zephyra. The wind returned, gentler now, like a sigh of forgiveness. *'The sky is not yours to rule,'* the eagle said, *'but yours to sing with, not against.'*

    Mira returned to the village, and Zephyra swirled around her, warm and alive. And the storms, at last, moved not with arrogance, but with grace.

    To this day, when the wind rustles through the trees at dusk, the old ones say it is Mira, not forcing the air, but *dancing* with it—reminded that even the strongest voices must learn to listen.
  "
}
